article.description:
Seimone Augustus scored 17 points as No. 3
LSU defeated Southeastern Louisiana 93-52 Sunday.
article.headline: Depth the difference for LSU in its second win
article.linkText: No problem for LSU in easy win over SE Louisiana
article.story:
HAMMOND, La. (AP) -- Louisiana State used its entire roster to dispatch of
Southeastern Louisiana.

	   LSU (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today; No. 3 Associated Press) went on a 16-6 run early in the second half, and
Seimone Augustus, scored 17 points to lead the way to a
93-52 victory Sunday over Southeastern Louisiana.

	   ''What you'll see during the season is us going to the bench
early,'' LSU coach Sue Gunter said. ''It's a pattern that will
develop as we go down the stretch and deeper into the season.

	   ''It shouldn't make any difference what five are on the floor
because all of these kids can play.''

	   LSU used all 13 players and all but one scored at least two
points.

	   ''To me it was very pretty to watch the team as we
substituted,'' Gunter said. ''You just saw everybody just continue
to keep their level of play very high and it didn't matter what
five we had on the floor.''

	   DeTrina White and Temeka Johnson each scored 12 for LSU, which
led 40-32 at halftime. White was 4-for-5 from the field and hit all
four of her free throws. Augustus hit eight of 10 of her shots.

	   LSU (2-0) outscored Southeastern (1-1) 53-20 in the second half
and finished the game on a 22-2 run. In the second half,
Southeastern was scoreless for 10 minutes, hitting just less than 30
percent of its shots.

	   Ke-ke Tardy and Roneeka Hodges each scored 10 points, and
Wendlyn Jones had six points and a game-high eight rebounds. All
three players came on in reserve.

	   ''We are going to have to do this,'' Gunter said. ''We are going
to need about 10 or 11 players that are going to have to play for
us going down the stretch.''

	   Melissa Williams scored 12 points on four 3-pointers for
Southeastern, while Tish Guy added 10 points.

	   LSU hit 63.2 percent of its shots in the second half and
outrebounded Southeastern 43-26 for the game.

	   ''They were putting up some shots, like no one else could
make,'' Johnson said. ''Some of them were good shots, but it just
proved that everybody's going to come after us.''

	   LSU's defense forced 22 turnovers and held the Lady Lions to
36.2 percent shooting from the floor for the game.

	   ''We were prepared for the game and ready to play and we got
after it in the first half,'' said Southeastern's Shanna Achord,
who scored her eight points in the first nine minutes. ''We were
hitting shots ... making everything. In the second half we came out
and I think LSU kind of woke up and came back. That's not an
excuse. We should have defended them better.''

	   In the first half, LSU jumped out to an early 18-8 lead, but
Southeastern went on a 7-2 run and tied the game at 28-28 on a
jumper by Pam Mathews with 4:14 left. But the Lady Tigers finished
the half on 8-2 run.
